{{Infobox film | name = Ikiru | image = Ikiru poster.jpg | caption = Theatrical release poster | director = [[Akira Kurosawa]] | producer = [[Sōjirō Motoki]] | screenplay = {{Plainlist| * Akira Kurosawa * [[Shinobu Hashimoto]] * [[Hideo Oguni]] }} | starring = {{Plainlist| * [[Takashi Shimura]] * Miki Odagiri }} | music = [[Fumio Hayasaka]] | cinematography = [[Asakazu Nakai]] | editing = Kōichi Iwashita | distributor = [[Toho]] | released = {{Film date|1952|10|9}} | runtime = 143 minutes | country = Japan | language = Japanese | budget = }}
{{nihongo|'''''Ikiru'''''|生きる||"To Live"}} is a 1952 Japanese [[Drama (film and television)|drama film]] directed and co-written by [[Akira Kurosawa]] and starring [[Takashi Shimura]]. The film examines the struggles of a terminally ill [[Tokyo]] bureaucrat and his final quest for meaning. The screenplay was partly inspired by [[Leo Tolstoy]]'s 1886 novella ''[[The Death of Ivan Ilyich]]''.
The major themes of the film include learning how to live, the inefficiency of [[bureaucracy]], and decaying family life in Japan, which have been the subject of analysis by academics and critics. The film has received widespread critical acclaim, and in Japan won awards for Best Film at the [[Kinema Junpo]] and [[Mainichi Film Awards]]. It was remade as a television film in 2007.
==Plot== Kanji Watanabe is a [[middle-aged]] man who has worked in the same monotonous [[bureaucrat]]ic position for thirty years. His wife is dead and his son and daughter-in-law, who live with him, seem to care mainly about Watanabe's pension and their future inheritance. At work, he's a party to constant bureaucratic inaction. In one case, a group of parents are seemingly endlessly referred to one department after another when they want a cesspool cleared out and replaced by a [[playground]]. After learning he has [[stomach cancer]] and less than a year to live, Watanabe attempts to come to terms with his impending death. He plans to tell his son about the cancer, but decides against it when his son does not pay attention to him. He then tries to find escape in the pleasures of Tokyo's nightlife, guided by an eccentric novelist whom he has just met. In a nightclub, Watanabe requests a song from the piano player, and sings "[[Gondola no Uta]]" with great sadness. His singing greatly affects those watching him. After one night submerged in the nightlife, he realizes this is not the solution.
The following day, Watanabe encounters a young female subordinate, Toyo, who needs his signature on her resignation. He takes comfort in observing her joyous love of life and enthusiasm and tries to spend as much time as possible with her. She eventually becomes suspicious of his intentions and grows weary of him. After convincing her to join him for the last time, he opens up and asks for the secret to her love of life. She says that she does not know, but that she found happiness in her new job making toys, which makes her feel like she is playing with all the children of Japan. Inspired by her, Watanabe realizes that it is not too late for him to do something significant. Like Toyo, he wants to make something, but is unsure what he can do within the city bureaucracy until he remembers the lobbying for a playground. He surprises everyone by returning to work after a long absence, and begins pushing for a playground despite concerns he is intruding on the jurisdiction of other departments.
Watanabe dies, and at his wake, his former co-workers gather, after the opening of the playground, and try to figure out what caused such a dramatic change in his behavior. His transformation from listless bureaucrat to passionate advocate puzzles them. As the co-workers drink, they slowly realize that Watanabe must have known he was dying, even when his son denies this, as he was unaware of his father's condition. They also hear from a witness that in the last few moments in Watanabe's life, he sat on the swing at the park he built. As the snow fell, he sang "Gondola no Uta". The bureaucrats vow to live their lives with the same dedication and passion as he did. But back at work, they lack the courage of their newfound conviction.
==Cast== {{multiple image | align = right | direction = horizontal | footer = [[Takashi Shimura]] and [[Haruo Tanaka]] have starring roles. | footer_align = left | width = | image1 = Shimura Takashi.JPG | width1 = 154 | alt1 = | image2 = Tanaka Haruo.JPG | width2 = 150 | alt2 = }} {{Cast listing| * [[Takashi Shimura]] as {{nihongo|Kanji Watanabe|渡邊 勘治|''Watanabe Kanji''}} * [[Shinichi Himori]] as {{nihongo|Kimura|木村}} * [[Haruo Tanaka]] as {{nihongo|Sakai|坂井}} * [[Minoru Chiaki]] as {{nihongo|Noguchi|野口}} * Miki Odagiri as {{nihongo|Toyo Odagiri|小田切 とよ|''Odagiri Toyo''}} * [[Bokuzen Hidari]] as {{nihongo|Ohara|小原}} * Minosuke Yamada as Subordinate Clerk {{nihongo|Saito|齋藤}} * [[Kamatari Fujiwara]] as Sub-Section Chief {{nihongo|Ōno|大野}} * Makoto Kobori as {{nihongo|Kiichi Watanabe|渡邊 喜一|''Watanabe Kiichi''}}, Kanji's brother. * [[Nobuo Kaneko]] as {{nihongo|Mitsuo Watanabe|渡邊 光男|''Watanabe Mitsuo''}}, Kanji's son. * [[Nobuo Nakamura]] as the Deputy Mayor. * [[Atsushi Watanabe (actor)|Atsushi Watanabe]] as a patient at the hospital. * [[Isao Kimura]] as a medical intern. * Masao Shimizu as the doctor. * [[Yūnosuke Itō]] as the novelist. * Kyoko Seki as {{nihongo|Kazue Watanabe|渡邊 一枝|''Watanabe Kazue''}}, Kanji's daughter-in-law. * Kumeko Urabe as {{nihongo|Tatsu Watanabe|渡邊 たつ|''Watanabe Tatsu''}}, Kiichi's wife. * [[Noriko Honma]] as a housewife. * [[Seiji Miyaguchi]] as the [[Yakuza]] boss. * [[Daisuke Katō]] as a [[Yakuza]]. }}
==Themes==
===Living=== Death is a major theme in the film, which leads to the protagonist Watanabe's quest to find the meaning of life.<ref name="Sesonske">{{Cite web|url=https://www.criterion.com/current/posts/839-ikiru |title=Ikiru |last=Sesonske |first=Alexander |date=19 November 1990 |accessdate=19 December 2016 |work=[[The Criterion Collection]]}}</ref> Initially, Watanabe looks to nightclubs and women to live life to the fullest, but winds up singing the 1915 song "[[Gondola no Uta]]" as an expression of loss.{{sfn|Thomas|2011}} Professor Alexander Sesonske writes that in the nightclub scene, Watanabe realizes "pleasure is not life," and that a goal gives him new happiness, with the song "[[Happy Birthday to You]]" symbolizing his rebirth.<ref name="Sesonske"/> Because Toyo is young, she has the best insight as to how to live, and is presented as the "unlikely savior" in Watanabe's "redemption."{{sfn|Thomas|2011}}
Author [[Donald Richie]] wrote that the title of the film, meaning simply "to live," could signify that "existence is enough." However, Watanabe finds existence is painful, and takes this as inspiration, wanting to ensure his life has not been futile. The justification of his life, found in his park, is how Watanabe discovered how "to live."<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.criterion.com/current/posts/307-ikiru |title=Ikiru |last=Richie |first=Donald |date=5 January 2004 |accessdate=19 December 2016 |work=[[The Criterion Collection]]}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Yamada|first=Seiji|last2=Maskarinec|first2=Gregory|last3=Greene|first3=Gordon|date=2003|title=Cross-Cultural Ethics and the Moral Development of Physicians: Lessons from Kurosawa’s Ikiru.|url=https://www.stfm.org/fmhub/fm2003/mar03/lame.pdf|journal=Family Medicine|volume=35|pages=167–169|via=}}</ref> In the end, Watanabe now sings "Gondola no Uta" with great contentment.{{sfn|Thomas|2011}}
===Bureaucracy=== ''Ikiru'' is also an "indictment of [[Civil service of Japan|Japanese bureaucracy]]."<ref name="Sesonske"/> In Japan after [[World War II]], it was expected that the [[sararīman]] (salary man) would work predictably in accordance with an organization's rules.{{sfn|Brannigan|2009|p=347}} The scene where the mothers first visit the city office requesting a playground shows "unconcern" in the bureaucrats, who send the visitors on a "farcical runaround," before asking them for a written request, with paperwork in the film symbolizing "meaningless activity."{{sfn|Brannigan|2009|p=354-355}} Despite this, Watanabe uses the bureaucracy to forge his legacy, and is apparently not disturbed when the bureaucracy quickly forgets he drove the project to build the playground.{{sfn|Lucken|2016|p=113}}
[[Health care system in Japan|Japanese health care]] is also depicted as overly bureaucratic in the film, as Watanabe visits a clinic in a "poignant" scene.{{sfn|Brannigan|2009|p=345}} The doctor is portrayed as paternalistic, and Watanabe does not stand up to his authority.{{sfn|Brannigan|2009|p=355}}
===Family life=== Author Timothy Iles writes that, as with [[Yasujirō Ozu]]'s 1953 film ''[[Tokyo Story]]'', ''Ikiru'' may hold a negative view about the state of family life in modern Japan. Watanabe has lived with his son for years, but they have fallen out of any true relationship. His son, Mitsuo, sees Watanabe as a bother, and sees him as standing in the way of money in Watanabe's [[will and testament|will]].{{sfn|Iles|2008|p=83}} The children fall short of their responsibility to respect their parents.{{sfn|Iles|2008|p=84}}
Urbanization may be a reason for negative changes in Japanese society, although a reason for Watanabe and Mitsuo's drift is also Watanabe's preoccupation with work.{{sfn|Iles|2008|p=84}} Another reason is Watanabe not being with Mitsuo during a medical treatment when the boy was 10, which fits a pattern in Kurosawa's films of sons being overly harsh to their fathers.{{sfn|Vicari|2016|p=72}}
==Production== {{multiple image | align = right | direction = horizontal | footer = [[Leo Tolstoy]]'s ''[[The Death of Ivan Ilyich]]'' was an inspiration for the screenplay, co-written by [[Hideo Oguni]]. | footer_align = left | width = | image1 = Leo Tolstoy, portrait.jpg | width1 = 140 | alt1 = | image2 = Oguni Hideo.JPG | width2 = 195 | alt2 = }} The film marked the first collaboration between director [[Akira Kurosawa]] and screenwriter [[Hideo Oguni]]. According to Oguni, the genesis of the film was Kurosawa's desire to make a film about a man who knows he is going to die, and wants a reason to live for a short time.<ref name="Mcgee">{{cite web|url=http://www.tcm.com/this-month/article/290046%7c0/Ikiru.html|title=Ikiru |last=McGee |first=Scott |date=|work=[[Turner Classic Movies]]|accessdate=18 December 2016}}</ref> Oguni was an experienced writer and was offered ¥500,000, while co-writer [[Shinobu Hashimoto]] was offered ¥150,000. Initially, Kurosawa told Hashimoto that a man who was set to die in 75 days had to be the theme, and that the character's career was less important, with the director saying criminal, homeless man or government minister would be acceptable.{{sfn|Hashimoto|2015}}
The screenwriters consulted [[Leo Tolstoy]]'s novella ''[[The Death of Ivan Ilyich]]'', and Oguni envisioned placing Watanabe's death halfway through the film.<ref name="Mcgee"/> Kurosawa dictated the scene where Watanabe is on the swing, and mentioned the beginning lyrics of "[[Gondola no Uta]]." Since none of the men were familiar with the song, they consulted their eldest receptionist on the rest of the lyrics and the song title.{{sfn|Hashimoto|2015}}
Kurosawa renamed the draft ''The Life of Kanji Watanabe'' to ''Ikiru'', which Hashimoto found pretentious, but Oguni supported. The screenplay was completed on 5 February 1952.{{sfn|Hashimoto|2015}}
==Release== In Japan, [[Toho]] released the film on 9 October 1952.{{sfn|Galbraith|2008|p=88}} The film was also screened in the [[4th Berlin International Film Festival|1954 Berlin International Film Festival]].<ref name="Berlinale 1954">{{cite web |url=http://www.berlinale.de/en/archiv/jahresarchive/1954/02_programm_1954/02_Programm_1954.html |title=PROGRAMME 1954 |accessdate=18 December 2016 |work=[[Berlin International Film Festival]]}}</ref>
In the United States, the film was shown for a short time in California in 1956, under the title ''Doomed''.<ref name="Mcgee"/> It opened as ''Ikiru'' in [[New York City]] on 29 January 1960.<ref name="Crowther">{{Cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/movie/review?res=9A0DE1DA143EEF3ABC4850DFB766838B679EDE |title=Screen: Drama Imported From Japan:'Ikiru' Has Premiere at the Little Carnegie Shimura Stars as Petty Government Aide |last=Crowther |first=Bosley |date=30 January 1960 |accessdate=18 December 2016 |work=[[The New York Times]]}}</ref> The film poster featured the [[stripper]] seen briefly in the film, rather than Watanabe.<ref name="Mcgee"/>
==Reception==
===Critical reception=== [[File:Ikiru 1.jpg|thumb|right|180px|[[Takashi Shimura]] as Kanji Watanabe in the iconic scene.]] The film won critical approval upon its release.{{sfn|Lucken|2016|p=108}} [[Bosley Crowther]], writing for ''[[The New York Times]]'', called it "a strangely fascinating and affecting film, up to a point—that being the point where it consigns its aged hero to the great beyond," which he deemed "anti-climactic." Crowther praised Shimura, saying he "measures up through his performance in this picture with the top film actors anywhere," and complimented Miki Odagiri, Nobuo Kaneko and Yunosuke Ito.<ref name="Crowther"/> ''[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]'' staff called the film "a tour-de-force," by "keeping a dramatic thread throughout and avoiding the mawkish."<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://variety.com/1951/film/reviews/ikiru-1200417247/ |title=Review: 'Ikiru' |last=Variety Staff |first= |date=31 December 1951 |accessdate=18 December 2016 |work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]}}</ref>
[[Roger Ebert]] added it to his list of [[The Great Movies|Great Movies]] in 1996, saying, "Over the years I have seen ''Ikiru'' every five years or so, and each time it has moved me, and made me think. And the older I get, the less Watanabe seems like a pathetic old man, and the more he seems like every one of us."<ref name= "ebertikiru">{{cite news | last = Ebert | first = Roger | coauthors = | title = ''Ikiru :: rogerebert.com :: Great Movies'' | work = | pages = | language = | publisher = [[Chicago Sun-Times]] | date = September 29, 1996 | url = http://rogerebert.suntimes.com/apps/pbcs.dll/article?AID=/19960929/REVIEWS08/401010329/1023 | accessdate =18 December 2016 }}</ref> In his Great Movies review of ''[[Seven Samurai]]'', Ebert called it Kurosawa's greatest film.<ref name= "ebertseven">{{cite news | last = Ebert | first = Roger | coauthors = | title = ''The Seven Samurai :: rogerebert.com :: Great Movies'' | work = | pages = | language = | publisher = [[Chicago Sun-Times]] | date = August 19, 2001 | url = http://rogerebert.suntimes.com/apps/pbcs.dll/article?AID=/20010819/REVIEWS08/401010356/1023 | accessdate = 2010-01-16 }}</ref> In 2008, Wally Hammond of ''[[Time Out (magazine)|Time Out]]'' praised ''Ikiru'' as "one of the triumphs of humanist cinema."<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.timeout.com/london/film/ikiru |title=Ikiru |last=Hammond |first=Wally |date=15 July 2008 |accessdate=19 December 2016 |work=[[Time Out (magazine)|Time Out]]}}</ref> That year, ''[[The New Yorker]]'''s [[Michael Sragow]] described it as a "masterwork," noting Kurosawa was usually associated more with his [[action film]]s.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.newyorker.com/magazine/2008/08/04/movies-59 |title=Movies |last=Sragow |first=Michael |date=4 August 2008 |accessdate=19 December 2016 |work=[[The New Yorker]]}}</ref> The scene featuring Watanabe on the [[swing (seat)|swing]] in the playground he built has been described as "iconic."<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/culture/film/filmmakersonfilm/3648271/Film-makers-on-film-Scott-Derrickson.html |title=Film-makers on film: Scott Derrickson |last=Sooke |first=Alistair |date=26 November 2005 |accessdate=19 December 2016 |work=[[The Daily Telegraph]]}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.slantmagazine.com/house/article/ikiru-akira-kurosawa-1952 |title=Ikiru (Akira Kurosawa, 1952) |last=Jardine |first=Dan |date=23 March 2010 |accessdate=19 December 2016 |work=[[Slant Magazine]]}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.christianitytoday.com/ct/2016/february-web-only/year-in-liturgical-cinema-ash-wednesday-lent.html?amp;utm_medium=feed&amp;utm_campaign=Feed%3A+christianitytoday%2Fctmag+&start=2 |title=The Year in Liturgical Cinema: Ash Wednesday and Lent |last=Mayward |first=Joel |date=10 February 2016 |accessdate=19 December 2016 |work=[[Christianity Today]]}}</ref>
''[[Empire (film magazine)|Empire]]'' magazine ranked ''Ikiru'' ranks 459th on its 2008 list of the 500 greatest movies of all time,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.empireonline.com/500/8.asp|title=The 500 Greatest Movies Of All Time|author=|date=3 October 2008|work=[[Empire (film magazine)|Empire]]|accessdate=18 December 2016}}</ref> and 44th in "The 100 Best Films Of World Cinema" in 2010.<ref>{{cite web| title = The 100 Best Films Of World Cinema – 44. Ikiru | url = http://www.empireonline.com/features/100-greatest-world-cinema-films/default.asp?film=44| work = [[Empire (film magazine)|Empire]]|date=11 June 2010 |accessdate=18 December 2016}}</ref> Conversely, in 2016 ''[[The Daily Telegraph]]'' named it one of the 10 most overrated films.<ref>{{cite web|first1=Tim|last1=Robey|title=10 most overrated films of all time|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/films/2016/08/06/the-10-most-overrated-films-of-all-time/ |work=[[The Daily Telegraph]]|publisher=[[Telegraph Media Group]]|date=6 August 2016|accessdate=19 December 2016}}</ref> The film has a 100% positive rating from critics at the review aggregator website [[Rotten Tomatoes]], based on 32 reviews.<ref name="RTfresh">{{cite web|url=http://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/ikiru/|title=Ikiru |publisher=[[Rotten Tomatoes]]|accessdate=18 December 2016}}</ref>
===Accolades=== The film competed for the [[Golden Bear]] at the [[4th Berlin International Film Festival]] in 1954.<ref name="Berlinale 1954"/>
{| class="wikitable plainrowheaders sortable" |- ! scope="col"| Award ! scope="col"| Date of ceremony ! scope="col"| Category ! scope="col"| Recipient(s) ! scope="col"| Result ! scope="col" class="unsortable"| {{Abbr|Ref(s)|Reference(s)}} |- ! scope="row"| [[British Academy Film Awards|BAFTA Awards]] | [[13th British Academy Film Awards|1960]] | Best Foreign Actor | [[Takashi Shimura]] | {{nom}} | rowspan="1" | <ref>{{Cite web|url=http://awards.bafta.org/award/1960/film |title=Film in 1960 |last= |first= |date= |accessdate=18 December 2016 |work=[[British Academy of Film and Television Arts]]}}</ref> |- ! scope="row"| [[Berlin International Film Festival]] | [[4th Berlin International Film Festival|18–29 June 1954]] | Special Prize of the Senate of Berlin | rowspan="3" | [[Akira Kurosawa]] | {{won}} | rowspan="1" | {{sfn|Galbraith|2008|p=88}} |- ! scope="row"| [[Kinema Junpo|Kinema Junpo Awards]] | 1953 | [[Kinema Junpo Award for Best Film of the Year|Best Film]] | {{won}} | rowspan="1" | {{sfn|Galbraith|2008|p=88}} |- !scope="row" rowspan=3| [[Mainichi Film Awards]] | rowspan="3" | 1953 | [[Mainichi Film Award for Best Film|Best Film]] | {{won}} | rowspan="3" | {{sfn|Galbraith|2008|p=88}} |- | [[Mainichi Film Award for Best Screenplay|Best Screenplay]] | Akira Kurosawa, [[Shinobu Hashimoto]] and [[Hideo Oguni]] | {{won}} |- | [[Mainichi Film Award for Best Sound Recording|Best Sound Recording]] | [[Fumio Yanoguchi]] | {{won}} |- ! scope="row"| [[Ministry of Education, Culture, Sports, Science and Technology|Ministry of Education]] | 1953 | Minister of Education Award ! | {{won}} | rowspan="1" | {{sfn|Galbraith|2008|p=88}} |- |}
==Legacy== Kurosawa believed [[William Shakespeare]]'s play ''[[Macbeth]]'' could serve as a [[cautionary tale]] complementing ''Ikiru'', thus directing his 1957 film ''[[Throne of Blood]]''.{{sfn|Richie|1998|p=115}} ''Ikiru'' was remade as a Japanese [[television film]] that debuted on [[TV Asahi]] on 9 September 2007, the day after a remake of Kurosawa's ''[[High and Low (1963 film)|High and Low]]''. The ''Ikiru'' remake stars [[kabuki]] actor [[Matsumoto Kōshirō IX]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.japantimes.co.jp/culture/2007/09/02/tv/environmental-celebrity-special-celebrity-comeback-special-kurosawa-classic-adaptation/#.WFdx__krLIU |title=Environmental celebrity special, celebrity comeback special, Kurosawa classic adaptation |last= |first= |date=2 September 2007 |accessdate=18 December 2016 |work=[[The Japan Times]]}}</ref>
''[[Anand (1971 film)|Anand]]'', a 1971 [[Cinema of India|Indian]] [[Hindi film]], was loosely inspired by ''Ikiru''.{{sfn|Raghavendra|2014|p=200}} In 2003, [[DreamWorks]] attempted to make a U.S. remake, which would star [[Tom Hanks]] in the lead role, and talked to [[Richard Price (writer)|Richard Price]] about adapting the screenplay.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://variety.com/2003/film/markets-festivals/price-right-for-ikiru-1117883385/ |title=Price right for 'Ikiru' |last=Fleming |first=Michael |date=24 March 2003 |accessdate=18 December 2016 |work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]}}</ref> [[Jim Sheridan]] agreed to direct the film in 2004,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://variety.com/2004/film/markets-festivals/irish-eyes-smile-on-dreamworks-ikiru-remake-1117910213/ |title=Irish eyes smile on DreamWorks' 'Ikiru' remake |last1=Fleming |first1=Michael |last2=LaPorte |first2=Nicole |date=9 September 2004 |accessdate=18 December 2016 |work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]}}</ref> though it has not been produced.
